# DDD: File Length and Atomicity

This rule establishes file size limits and atomicity requirements for all Domain-Driven Design components. The goal is to maintain code that is focused, readable, and maintainable while allowing flexibility for complex domain logic.

## Rationale

- **Focused files are easier to understand** - Smaller files with single responsibility are easier to reason about
- **Atomicity improves maintainability** - One component per file makes code easier to find and modify
- **Size limits prevent god classes** - Enforcing limits encourages proper decomposition
- **Flexible limits accommodate complexity** - Domain logic sometimes requires more space than UI components
- **Single Responsibility Principle** - Each file should have one clear purpose
- **Documented exceptions allow pragmatism** - Complex aggregates and services can exceed limits with justification

## Core Principles

1. **One primary component per file** - Each file exports exactly one main DDD component
2. **Single Responsibility Principle** - Each file has one clear purpose
3. **Flexible size limits** - Limits accommodate domain complexity while preventing bloat
4. **Extract when approaching limits** - Refactor before hitting limits
5. **Document exceptions** - Complex components exceeding limits require clear justification

## File Length Limits

### Standard Limits

Maximum lines of code for each DDD component type:

| Component Type | Standard Limit | Exception Limit | Rationale |
|---------------|----------------|-----------------|-----------|
| **Value Objects** | 300 LOC | 400 LOC | Simple validation and behavior |
| **Entities** | 300 LOC | 400 LOC | Identity and core behavior |
| **Aggregates** | 500 LOC | 600 LOC | Complex invariants and coordination |
| **Use Cases** | 300 LOC | 400 LOC | Single business workflow |
| **Domain Services** | 400 LOC | 500 LOC | Pure business logic |
| **Application Services** | 400 LOC | 500 LOC | Orchestration logic |
| **Repositories** | 400 LOC | 500 LOC | Persistence operations |
| **DTOs** | 200 LOC | 250 LOC | Data transfer structures |
| **Event Handlers** | 300 LOC | 400 LOC | Event processing logic |
| **Factories** | 300 LOC | 400 LOC | Complex object creation |
| **Specifications** | 200 LOC | 300 LOC | Business rule encapsulation |

### ✅ CORRECT - Components within limits

```typescript
// packages/events/domain/value-objects/title.ts (~60 LOC)
import { OneJsError } from '@OneJs/Core'
import { ErrorCodes } from '@OneJs/shared-errors'

export class Title {
  private constructor(private readonly value: string) {}

  static create(value: string): Title {
    if (!value || value.trim().length === 0) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Title cannot be empty',
        400,
        'Event title is required',
        undefined,
        ErrorCodes.VALIDATION_FAILED
      )
    }

    if (value.length > 200) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Title too long',
        400,
        'Event title must not exceed 200 characters',
        { length: value.length },
        ErrorCodes.VALIDATION_FAILED
      )
    }

    return new Title(value.trim())
  }

  static createFrom(value: string): Title {
    if (!value || value.trim().length === 0) {
      throw new OneJsError('Title cannot be empty', 400)
    }
    return new Title(value.trim())
  }

  toString(): string {
    return this.value
  }

  equals(other: Title): boolean {
    return this.value === other.value
  }
}
```

```typescript
// packages/events/application/use-cases/create-event.use-case.ts (~80 LOC)
import { Inject, Injectable } from '@OneJs'
import { EventBus } from '@OneJs/EventBus'
import { Event } from '@events/domain/entities'
import { EventPrismaRepository } from '@events/infrastructure/repositories'
import type { CreateEventDto } from '../dtos'

@Injectable()
export class CreateEventUseCase {
  constructor(
    @Inject(EventPrismaRepository)
    private readonly eventRepository: EventPrismaRepository,
    @Inject(EventBus)
    private readonly eventBus: EventBus,
  ) {}

  async execute(dto: CreateEventDto): Promise<Event> {
    // Create event entity with validation
    const event = Event.create({
      title: dto.title,
      description: dto.description,
      startDate: dto.startDate,
      cityId: dto.cityId,
      venueId: dto.venueId,
    })

    // Persist event
    const savedEvent = await this.eventRepository.save(event)

    // Publish domain event
    await this.eventBus.publish(new EventCreatedEvent(savedEvent.toEventDto()))

    return savedEvent
  }
}
```

