## Extraction Guidelines

When approaching or exceeding limits, follow these extraction strategies:

### 1. Extract Helper Methods First

Move repeated logic to private methods within the same class:

```typescript
// Before: Inline logic repeated multiple times
export class Event {
  validate(): void {
    if (!this.title || this.title.length === 0) {
      throw new Error('Title required')
    }
    if (this.title.length > 200) {
      throw new Error('Title too long')
    }
    
    if (!this.description || this.description.length === 0) {
      throw new Error('Description required')
    }
    if (this.description.length > 1000) {
      throw new Error('Description too long')
    }
  }
}

// After: Extract to helper methods
export class Event {
  validate(): void {
    this.validateTitle()
    this.validateDescription()
  }

  private validateTitle(): void {
    if (!this.title || this.title.length === 0) {
      throw new Error('Title required')
    }
    if (this.title.length > 200) {
      throw new Error('Title too long')
    }
  }

  private validateDescription(): void {
    if (!this.description || this.description.length === 0) {
      throw new Error('Description required')
    }
    if (this.description.length > 1000) {
      throw new Error('Description too long')
    }
  }
}
```

### 2. Extract Validation to Value Objects

Move validation logic from entities to value objects:

```typescript
// Before: Validation in entity (~200 LOC)
export class User {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: UserId,
    private email: string,
    private username: string,
  ) {
    // 50+ lines of email validation
    // 50+ lines of username validation
  }
}

// After: Extract to value objects (~80 LOC entity + 60 LOC each VO)
export class User {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: UserId,
    private email: Email,      // Value object handles validation
    private username: Username, // Value object handles validation
  ) {}
}

// packages/user/domain/value-objects/email.ts (~60 LOC)
export class Email {
  private constructor(private readonly value: string) {}

  static create(value: string): Email {
    // Email validation logic
    return new Email(value)
  }
}

// packages/user/domain/value-objects/username.ts (~60 LOC)
export class Username {
  private constructor(private readonly value: string) {}

  static create(value: string): Username {
    // Username validation logic
    return new Username(value)
  }
}
```

### 3. Extract Business Logic to Domain Services

Move complex business logic from entities to domain services:

```typescript
// Before: Complex pricing logic in entity (~300 LOC)
export class Event {
  calculatePrice(tier: PricingTier, quantity: number): Money {
    // 100+ lines of complex pricing calculations
    // Discounts, taxes, fees, promotions
  }
}

// After: Extract to domain service (~100 LOC entity + 200 LOC service)
export class Event {
  calculatePrice(
    tier: PricingTier,
    quantity: number,
    pricingService: EventPricingDomainService,
  ): Money {
    return pricingService.calculateEventPrice(this, tier, quantity)
  }
}

// packages/events/domain/services/event-pricing.service.ts (~200 LOC)
@Injectable()
export class EventPricingDomainService {
  calculateEventPrice(
    event: Event,
    tier: PricingTier,
    quantity: number,
  ): Money {
    // Complex pricing calculations
  }
}
```

### 4. Split Complex Use Cases

Break large use cases into smaller, focused use cases:

```typescript
// Before: Large use case handling multiple operations (~400 LOC)
@Injectable()
export class ProcessEventUseCase {
  async execute(eventId: string): Promise<void> {
    // 100+ lines: Process event
    // 100+ lines: Send notifications
    // 100+ lines: Update analytics
    // 100+ lines: Invalidate caches
  }
}

// After: Split into focused use cases (~100 LOC each)
@Injectable()
export class ProcessEventUseCase {
  async execute(eventId: string): Promise<void> {
    // Core event processing only
  }
}

@Injectable()
export class NotifyEventSubscribersUseCase {
  async execute(eventId: string): Promise<void> {
    // Notification logic
  }
}

@Injectable()
export class TrackEventAnalyticsUseCase {
  async execute(eventId: string): Promise<void> {
    // Analytics logic
  }
}

@Injectable()
export class InvalidateEventCacheUseCase {
  async execute(eventId: string): Promise<void> {
    // Cache invalidation logic
  }
}
```

### 5. Extract Query Logic to Specifications

Move complex query logic to specification pattern:

```typescript
// Before: Complex query logic in repository (~450 LOC)
@Injectable()
export class EventPrismaRepository extends PrismaRepository<'event'> {
  async findByCriteria(
    cityId?: string,
    startDate?: Date,
    endDate?: Date,
    categoryId?: string,
    tags?: string[],
    priceRange?: { min: number; max: number },
    // ... 10+ more filter parameters
  ): Promise<Event[]> {
    // 200+ lines of complex query building
  }
}

// After: Extract to specification (~250 LOC repo + 200 LOC spec)
@Injectable()
export class EventPrismaRepository extends PrismaRepository<'event'> {
  async findBySpecification(spec: EventSpecification): Promise<Event[]> {
    const query = spec.toQuery()
    const events = await this.prisma.event.findMany(query)
    return events.map(e => Event.fromDatabase(e))
  }
}

// packages/events/domain/specifications/event.specification.ts (~200 LOC)
export class EventSpecification {
  constructor(private readonly criteria: EventCriteria) {}

  toQuery(): Prisma.EventFindManyArgs {
    // Complex query building logic
  }
}
```

### 6. Extract Transformation Logic to Factories

Move complex object creation to factory pattern:

```typescript
// Before: Complex creation logic in entity (~250 LOC)
export class Event {
  static create(dto: CreateEventDto): Event {
    // 100+ lines of complex object construction
    // Validation, transformation, child entity creation
  }
}

// After: Extract to factory (~100 LOC entity + 150 LOC factory)
export class Event {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: EventId,
    private readonly title: Title,
    // ... other properties
  ) {}
}

// packages/events/domain/factories/event.factory.ts (~150 LOC)
@Injectable()
export class EventFactory {
  create(dto: CreateEventDto): Event {
    // Complex object construction logic
    const id = EventId.generate()
    const title = Title.create(dto.title)
    // ... more construction logic
    return new Event(id, title, /* ... */)
  }
}
```

## File Organization

Maintain clear structure with one component per file:

```
packages/<bounded-context>/
├── domain/
│   ├── entities/
│   │   ├── user.ts                    # One entity per file
│   │   └── post.ts
│   ├── value-objects/
│   │   ├── email.ts                   # One value object per file
│   │   ├── username.ts
│   │   └── user-id.ts
│   ├── aggregates/
│   │   └── order.ts                   # One aggregate root per file
│   ├── services/
│   │   ├── pricing.service.ts         # One domain service per file
│   │   └── scheduling.service.ts
│   ├── specifications/
│   │   └── event.specification.ts     # One specification per file
│   ├── factories/
│   │   └── event.factory.ts           # One factory per file
│   └── dtos/
│       ├── event.dto.ts               # Related DTOs can be in same file
│       └── event-event.dto.ts
├── application/
│   ├── use-cases/
│   │   ├── create-user.use-case.ts    # One use case per file
│   │   ├── update-user.use-case.ts
│   │   └── delete-user.use-case.ts
│   ├── services/
│   │   └── user-search.service.ts     # One application service per file
│   ├── handlers/
│   │   └── user-created.handler.ts    # One event handler per file
│   └── dtos/
│       ├── create-user.dto.ts
│       └── update-user.dto.ts
└── infrastructure/
    └── repositories/
        └── user-prisma.repository.ts  # One repository per file
```

### Naming Conventions

Files MUST be named to match their primary export:

- **Value Objects**: `email.ts` exports `Email`
- **Entities**: `user.ts` exports `User`
- **Aggregates**: `order.ts` exports `Order`
- **Use Cases**: `create-user.use-case.ts` exports `CreateUserUseCase`
- **Domain Services**: `pricing.service.ts` exports `PricingDomainService`
- **Application Services**: `user-search.service.ts` exports `UserSearchService`
- **Repositories**: `user-prisma.repository.ts` exports `UserPrismaRepository`
- **Event Handlers**: `user-created.handler.ts` exports `UserCreatedHandler`
- **Factories**: `event.factory.ts` exports `EventFactory`
- **Specifications**: `event.specification.ts` exports `EventSpecification`

## Related Components in Same File

Small helper types/interfaces may coexist with the main component when:

1. **Used only within that file** - Not exported or used elsewhere
2. **Closely coupled** - Tightly related to the main component
3. **Small size** - Less than 20 lines total
4. **Not reusable** - Specific to this component only

### ✅ CORRECT - Small helper types

```typescript
// packages/events/domain/value-objects/email.ts

// ✅ Small helper type used only in this file
type EmailValidationResult = {
  isValid: boolean
  error?: string
}

// ✅ Small helper type for internal use
type EmailParts = {
  localPart: string
  domain: string
}

export class Email {
  private constructor(private readonly value: string) {}

  static create(value: string): Email {
    const validation = this.validate(value)
    if (!validation.isValid) {
      throw new OneJsError('Invalid email', 400, validation.error)
    }
    return new Email(value.toLowerCase())
  }

  private static validate(value: string): EmailValidationResult {
    // Validation logic using helper types
  }

  private getParts(): EmailParts {
    const [localPart, domain] = this.value.split('@')
    return { localPart, domain }
  }
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Related DTOs in same file

```typescript
// packages/events/domain/dtos/event.dto.ts

// ✅ Related DTOs that are always used together
export type EventDto = {
  id: string
  title: string
  description: string
  schedule: EventScheduleDto
  pricing: EventPricingDto
}

export type EventScheduleDto = {
  startDate: string
  endDate: string
  venueId: string
}

export type EventPricingDto = {
  basePrice: number
  currency: string
  tiers: PricingTierDto[]
}

export type PricingTierDto = {
  name: string
  price: number
  quantity: number
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Large helper types

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Helper types too large (50+ lines)
type EmailValidationRules = {
  // 50+ lines of validation rules
  // Should be extracted to separate file or domain service
}

export class Email {
  // Email implementation
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Reusable types in same file

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Reusable type that should be separate
type ValidationResult = {
  isValid: boolean
  errors: string[]
}

export class Email {
  static create(value: string): Email {
    const validation: ValidationResult = this.validate(value)
    // ...
  }
}

// ❌ ValidationResult is reusable across multiple value objects
// Should be in shared types file: packages/shared/types/validation.ts
```

## PR Checklist

Before submitting a PR, verify:

- [ ] All DDD components are within size limits or have documented exceptions
- [ ] One primary component per file (entity, value object, use case, service, repository)
- [ ] File names match component names (kebab-case for files, PascalCase for classes)
- [ ] Complex logic extracted to appropriate helpers/services
- [ ] Exceptions include clear justification, LOC count, and review date
- [ ] Single Responsibility Principle maintained for all components
- [ ] Helper types/interfaces are small (< 20 lines) and file-specific
- [ ] No god classes or god files
- [ ] Extraction guidelines followed when approaching limits

## Rules Summary

### ✅ DO

- Keep value objects under 300 LOC
- Keep entities under 300 LOC
- Keep aggregates under 500 LOC
- Keep use cases under 300 LOC
- Keep services under 400 LOC
- Keep repositories under 400 LOC
- Have one primary component per file
- Extract logic when approaching limits
- Document exceptions with clear justification
- Follow Single Responsibility Principle
- Name files to match their primary export
- Extract validation to value objects
- Extract business logic to domain services
- Split complex use cases into smaller ones
- Use specifications for complex queries
- Use factories for complex object creation

### ❌ DON'T DO

- Don't exceed limits without documented justification
- Don't put multiple components in one file
- Don't mix entities, value objects, and services in one file
- Don't create god classes with multiple responsibilities
- Don't ignore extraction guidelines
- Don't use weak justifications for exceptions ("it's complex")
- Don't let use cases grow beyond single workflow
- Don't put domain logic in application services
- Don't put business logic in repositories
- Don't create files without clear single purpose

